KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Emperor hopes for better year following '95 disasters+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Emperor Akihito said Monday he hopes the new year will be more
fortunate than 1995, which was overshadowed in Japan by January's
Great Hanshin Earthquake and March's nerve gas attack on Tokyo
subways.
     In his New Year message, the 62-year-old emperor said, ''It is
my ardent wish that the new year will be a happy one for the Japanese
people as well as for all the people of the world.''
     He also said the year 1995 was ''deeply meaningful'' in that it
marked the 50th anniversary of the end of World War II, which
deepened awareness about the nation's past and renewed the desire for
peace.
     Expressing his concern for the tens of thousands of people in
western Japan whose lives have been affected by the massive
earthquake last January, the emperor said, ''I sincerely hope that
the devastated area will be restored without delay and that the
people may know some ease and comfort in their lives.''
     Almost 6,300 people were killed when the quake hit the port city
of Kobe and its vicinity in the small hours of Jan. 17 last year, and
some 800 have since died as a result of the temblor.
     Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko as well as Crown Prince
Naruhito and his wife Princess Masako, visited the devastated areas
in a bid to help boost the victims' morale.
     The imperial couple is considering attending a memorial service
for those who died in the disaster, to be held in Kobe on the first
anniversary of the quake.
     The emperor had to undergo surgery to remove a polyp from his
large intestine last June, but he and the empress were both spared
from other health troubles in 1995.
     No trips abroad are scheduled for 1996 but as last year, the
couple will visit a number of places across Japan.
     The crown prince and princess will celebrate their third wedding
anniversary in June.  The empress dowager, who is said to be healthy
despite an occasional cold, will celebrate her 92nd birthday this
year, making her the longest living empress dowager in Japanese
history.
     Princess Nori, the emperor's only daughter and the youngest of
his three children, who began taking a more prominent public role
last year by making her first official trip abroad to Brazil, will
turn 27 in April, an event that is certain to fuel speculation about
whether she is planning to marry.



