KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Japan-U.S. JV to build LRW disposal facility for Russia+

MOSCOW, Dec. 31 Kyodo

     A Japanese-U.S. joint venture has won a 25 million dollar order
for building a liquid radioactive waste (LRW) facility in Russia's
Far East, Itar-Tass news agency reported Sunday.
     The joint venture between Tomen Corp., a major Japanese trading
house, and Babcock and Wilcox Co., a U.S. power generation system
maker, will begin to implement the project soon, the news agency said.
     A formal contract is to be signed Friday.
     The joint venture will dispose of the Pacific Fleet's LRW and
the required funds will be fully assigned from Japan's 100 million
dollar aid package to help countries of the Commonwealth of
Independent States dismantle nuclear weapons.
     The facility is expected to be constructed at Vladivostok
shipyards and will be capable of processing 7,000 cubic meters of LRW
a year, Itar-Tass said.
     The bulk of work to build the facility is expected to be
completed by the time the leaders of the Group of Seven
industrialized nations and Russia meet in Moscow in April to discuss
nuclear security issues, it said.
     The Japanese government decided to assist Russia in building a
new LRW disposal facility immediately after the Pacific Fleet
discharged LRW, due to the dismantling of nuclear-powered submarines,
in October 1993.
     The realization of the project was stalled, however, due to
technical problems and difficulties in the selection of contract
companies.



