KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

More than 1,100 set to run in next general election+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     More than 1,100 people have already decided to run in the next
general election, the first poll for the House of Representatives
since a new system combining single-seat constituencies with
proportional representation was put into effect a year ago,
according to a Kyodo News survey.
     The final number of candidates could balloon to more than 2,000
from the 1,128 who say they have already made up their minds.
     Some 1,020 are now planning to run in the 300 single-seat
constituencies in the election, which is widely expected to be held
by the end of the year.
     The Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), the dominant group in the
ruling coalition, has already settled on 270 candidates for the
single-seat constituencies, while the main opposition Shinshinto (New
Frontier Party) has selected 230.
     The two parties are likely to clash head on in at least 190
constituencies.
     Meanwhile, the Social Democratic Party (SDP) and New Party
Sakigake, the LDP's partners in the tripartite coalition, are lagging
far behind the LDP and Shinshinto in their election preparations.
     For the 200-seat proportional representation race, only about
100 are already set to declare their candidacy.  Among them are 26
from the LDP and 42 from Shinshinto.
     The focus of the election will be whether the LDP or Shinshinto
will secure a majority.
     The outcome will likely determine the political landscape in
Japan for the next several years, deciding whether a bipolar picture
will emerge or the era of coalition will continue.
     The SDP, which is being wracked by disputes over its plan to
launch a new party, has secured only about 80 candidates for the
single-seat constituencies.
     Sakigake is also tardy in working out a candidate lineup, with
only 45 prospects secured so far for the single-seat portion.
     Displaying its usual swiftness in election preparations, the
Japanese Communist Party has decided on candidates for all the
constituencies and 35 for the proportional representation.



