<A NAME = "9"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Births down, deaths, divorces up in '95+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Births in Japan continued their 20-year downward trend in 1995,
while the number of deaths, inflated by January's huge earthquake,
topped 900,000 for the first time since 1950, the Health and Welfare
Ministry announced Sunday.
     Ministry estimates, based on population statistics reported
through October, showed that 1,193,000 babies were born in Japan in
1995, down about 45,000 from the previous year and resuming a slide
that began in 1973 and was only briefly interrupted last year.
     It was the second time, following 1993, that the number of
births in Japan dipped below 120,000 in one year.  The birthrate of
9.6 per 1,000 people also equals that for 1993 as the lowest recorded
ever.
     Some 40,000 more deaths were recorded in 1995 than the previous
year as the killer quake that leveled much of Kobe and the
surrounding area Jan. 17 and claimed thousands lives and an influenza
epidemic added to the 916,000 total for the year.
     A total of 784,000 marriages were recorded in 1995, an increase
of 1,000 over 1994.  But divorces increased by 5,000 in 1995 as
200,000 couples formally ended their marriages.
     The largest killer of the year was cancer, which claimed 263,000
lives in 1995, followed by cerebrovascular diseases at 148,000 and
heart diseases at 139,000, the ministry reported.



