January 1, 1996

NEC to build its 2nd microchip plant in U.S., paper says+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     NEC Corp. will start construction of its second U.S.
semiconductor plant in California as early as spring at a cost of 80
billion to 100 billion yen in a move aimed at taking the lead in the
global market for 256-megabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM)
chips, a business daily reported Monday.
     The Japanese electronics titan intends to begin operations of
the state-of-the-art plant by the end of 1998, the Nihon Kogyo
Shimbun said.
     The plant will be built at a 200,000-square-meter site adjacent
to the existing factory of NEC Electronics Inc., which is now
producing 4- and 16-megabit DRAMs, the paper said.  NEC has already
acquired the land plot for 400 million yen.
     The new factory will first mass-produce 64-megabit DRAMs and
plans to start churning out 256-megabit chips as early as 1998.  The
256-megabit chip is expected to become the mainstay semiconductor by
the end of this century.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "11"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

More men find joy of cooking: good side of dull economy?+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Maybe it is part of the recent trend in Japan to shift to a
plainer lifestyle in the prolonged recession, or it could be a sign
that more men recognize the need to be self-supporting later in life
as people live longer than before and as more women go out to work,
leaving their husbands at home.
     Or perhaps it is because there are more men living alone through
''tanshin funin'' -- transfer to another town while their families
stay behind for reasons such as children's school needs -- resulting
in the fathers having to take care of themselves.
     Whatever the cause, an increasing number of Japanese men are
discovering the joy of cooking.
     Although there are no official statistics, the trend can be seen
in the recent boom in cooking magazines that are targeted at men.
     Ryori-Tengoku magazine, started in February 1994 by a Tokyo
publisher, Ryori Tsushinsha Inc., has become one of the best-selling
magazines of its kind within two years.
     With articles about restaurants, well-known professional cooks
and their work as well as some of their recipes, the magazine now
sells more than 100,000 copies a month.
     Launched in December 1990 by another Tokyo publisher, President
Inc., the Danchu magazine promotes the concept of cooking as a man's
hobby and sells 240,000 copies.
     In an area where monthly sales of 50,000 copies are said to be
the threshold of success, the two magazines can be seen as clear hits.
     The common features of the two magazines are that both primarily
target men in their 30s or 40s, and the cover designs and layout of
pages are different from women's magazines about cookery.
     At book stores, both are likely to be found in the hobby-leisure
corner, not among books and magazines on housekeeping.
     Other evidence of the boom in men's cooking is seen in
television programs.  Among them, Fuji Television Network Inc.'s live
weekly show ''The Iron Men of Cooking'' scores a consistent 15-20%
audience rating by showing professional chefs competing with
each other to make several dishes within a given time.
     ''The gimmick of the program is to show the backstage process of
cooking, the sweat of the cooks and the drama of cooking,'' says
Toshihiko Matsuo, the producer of the program.  The three-year-old
program has now made stars of some of those chefs.
     In Japan, as has probably been common around the world, cooking
has traditionally been considered a women's activity.  Delving back
into history, such an attitude may stem from the conservative ideas
of Confucianism.
     The ancient Chinese philosophy was brought into Japan in the
fourth century and was favored by Japanese rulers throughout the
medieval period up to modern times, until at least the end of World
War II.
     One of the books on which Confucianism is based contains the
phrase ''Men should not enter the kitchen.''  Though many Japanese
today may have never read the book, they probably know the phrase.
     The saying reflects the Confucian emphasis on the importance
of maintaining clearly defined social roles and hierarchies, which
discouraged men from doing ''women's work'' and made those who wanted
to cook rather embarrassed.
     But in recent decades, attitudes have gradually changed.
Schools have begun letting boys take classes in basic living skills
together with girls.
     Moves toward women's liberation in the 1960s and 1970s also
contributed to the change.  Now, in the 1990s, with the rapid aging
of Japanese society, increasing calls are heard for men to become
more self-supporting.
     These trends of the times, along with the men's cooking
magazines and the TV programs, have encouraged men who love cooking
to come out of the closet.
     Danchu magazine organizes a ''Men's Original Cooking Contest''
every month, and once a year selects a grand winner who is awarded a
prize of 500,000 yen and a round-trip ticket for two overseas.
     The contest draws some 3,000 contestants a year, according to
the magazine, suggesting that men are no longer embarrassed to show
their cooking skills.
     ''I was surprised that one of my colleagues congratulated me
after I won Danchu's December contest,'' said Ryozo Nakamura, a
53-year-old mathematics teacher, ''because I did not expect that
readers of the magazine existed so close-by in my life.''
     For Nakamura, cooking was a daily necessity from his childhood
because his mother had poor health.  ''For a long time, it was
embarrassing to go to the supermarket because there were so few men
buying groceries,'' Nakamura says.
     But he continued cooking and actually found himself enjoying it
especially after he also became fond of fishing, he says.  His
winning recipe was a fish dish featuring snapper with burdock.
     Nakamura says the Danchu contest was not the only one he
entered, though it was the first in which he won a major prize.
     A recent article in a Japanese daily newspaper reported a rapid
increase in the number of men entering numerous cooking contests
around Japan.
     Some analysts say the boom is an effect of the ''bubble
economy'' of the 1980s.  Aside from the much-discussed negative
aspects of that period in Japan, it gave people opportunities to
taste materialistic luxuries such as buying high-quality brand goods,
taking overseas trips and eating out at gourmet restaurants.
     Of all these new pleasures, the habit of eating well is
something that people find difficult to abandon, the analysts say,
and so they became more interested in cooking at home.
     But some say men's enjoyment of cooking goes further back.
''The boom in cooking among men is not new at all,'' says Shigemasa
Kuroki, manager of a men's cooking group which was set up 18 years
ago and now has some 800 members across the nation.
     The group holds a monthly cooking session with 40 to 50 members
at a time, at which a professional cook teaches them on a completely
voluntary basis.  Because the group has existed for a long time,
teaching its members has become a prestige activity among some
professionals, Kuroki says.
     A 77-year-old member of the group said cooking is a tool that
helps him communicate with his grandchildren.  And perhaps it is also
spreading new ideas across the generations -- after all, the group's
name can be translated as ''Men in the Kitchen.''



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
