<A NAME = "12"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Governor advocates admitting foreigners to public service+

KOCHI, Japan, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     The governor of Kochi Prefecture on Japan's smallest main
island of Shikoku on Monday reiterated his intention to scrap this
year a regulation that makes Japanese nationality a prerequisite for
entry into prefectural public service.
     In his New Year's message, Gov. Daijiro Hashimoto said he has
gained the impression that allowing foreign nationals to sit for
entry exams for regular administrative posts ''does not have any
negative influence.''
     A number of local municipalities have hired foreigners in their
administrations, but so far the doors to the prefectural and national
public service have remained closed to non-Japanese.
     It remains to be seen how the governor will realize his plans
given that the Home Affairs Ministry remains skeptical, arguing that
the controversial nationality clause is based on the government's
interpretation of the Cabinet Law ''which is binding.''
     Exactly a year ago, Hashimoto, a reporter-turned politician and
half-brother of trade minister Ryutaro Hashimoto, first said he
wanted the clause scrapped so that foreigners may take entry exams
for nonmanagerial public-service posts.
     After encountering considerable resistance from within the
prefectural government, Hashimoto decided to postpone the move for a
year.
     The governor insists that local administrations must be seen as
a service industry and that anyone regardless of nationality can meet
the requirements of such duties ''if only the person is passionate
about his work.''
     Foreigners account for about 1% of Japan's 125 million
population.  Most of them are ethnic Koreans and Chinese who are
permanent residents, and many have been born in Japan.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "13"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Housing loan fiasco spells trouble for Murayama+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama faces a tough time over the
controversial government scheme to use 685 billion yen of taxpayers'
money to liquidate seven crippled housing loan companies.
     The 150-day regular Diet session is expected to convene Jan. 22,
primarily to discuss the government's 75.1 trillion yen budget
proposal for fiscal 1996 beginning April 1, under which the
liquidation scheme will be funded.
     Diet discussions on the housing loan companies' liquidation is
likely to be hot as the main opposition party Shinshinto (New
Frontier Party), backed up by taxpayers' frustration, will give
Murayama's tripartite coalition government a hard time on the issue.
     The government handout represents a burden of 5,500 yen for
every Japanese.
     Shinshinto says the use of tax money should not be allowed
without disclosure of information concerning the problem and pursuing
the responsibility of the government, the housing loan companies, the
banks which founded the crippled companies, and agricultural
financial institutions.
     Newly elected Shinshinto President Ichiro Ozawa pledges to
demand that Murayama dissolve the House of Representatives for a snap
general election immediately after the budget clears the Diet,
probably in late March or early April.
     The Japanese Communist Party also opposes the use of public
money and accuses the government of being responsible.
     Murayama, announcing the liquidation plan at a midnight press
conference Dec. 20, asked the public to support it.
     The prime minister said he has made a ''painful decision''
because the problem needs a swift solution in order to restore
domestic and overseas confidence in the Japanese financial system and
to invigorate the stagnant Japanese economy.
     Murayama pledged the government would do all it could to collect
money owed to the housing loan companies, vowing to thoroughly pursue
the responsibility of both their creditors and debtors.
     Finance Minister Masayoshi Takemura acknowledged his ministry's
responsibility in the problem of the housing loan companies, although
he did not state how the responsibility will be pursued.
     Shinshinto is expected to demand in the parliamentary debate
that Takemura resign.
     The opposition camp blames Murayama, who is chairman of the
Social Democratic Party (SDP), Takemura, head of the smallest
coalition force New Party Sakigake, and Ryutaro Hashimoto, trade
minister and president of the dominant Liberal Democratic Party (LDP).
     The mortgage companies extended massive amounts in loans to real
estate companies partly because housing loan lenders were exempted
from the March 1990 government restriction on loans to realtors.
     At that time Hashimoto was finance minister, and he has admitted
limited responsibility of ''politics'' as a result.
     The LDP hopes Hashimoto will succeed Murayama as prime minister,
but the criticism of him has begun to affect the prospect.
     Veteran LDP politician Seiroku Kajiyama said the next general
election should take place sometime later now because of the setback.
     Even some in the ruling camp advocate pursuing the
responsibility of the administrative staff at the finance and farm
ministries as well as the financial institutions and the debtor
realtors involved in the fiasco.
     LDP Secretary General Koichi Kato said, ''The public will not
consent until those concerned go behind bars.''
     The Diet is also expected to discuss the role of organized crime
in the scandal.  Some of the unrecoverable loans were to companies
connected with mobsters.
     Takemura promised to use ''every available means,'' in
cooperation with police and prosecutors, to recover as much as
possible of the loans in question.
     Ministers concerned, including Takemura, Justice Minister
Hiroshi Miyazawa and Home Affairs Minister Takashi Fukaya in his
capacity as National Public Safety Commission chairman, set up a
forum to discuss ways to collect the debts.
     The government vows to implement criminal investigations and seek
prosecution, if necessary, in the process of trying to collect the
loans.
     The coalition government promises to disclose information
related to the problem so that the public will understand why their
money is needed in the liquidation scheme.
     The public has been given only limited information on the
scandal.  No details have been released about the bad loans held by
the housing loan companies, such as names of debtors, or the role of
the companies' founding banks in the extension of the loans.








