<HR>
<A NAME = "14"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Mitsubishi to unveil low-priced teleconferencing system+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Mitsubishi Electric Corp. will introduce in the domestic market
as early as this month a new low-priced teleconferencing system that
is capable of transmitting motion pictures with telephone lines, an
industrial daily reported Monday.
     Using the broadband-integrated services digital network (B-ISDN)
of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., the system sends such
pictures by compressing them to 7 to 10 megabits per second, based on
the Motion Picture Experts Group-2, or MPEG-2, international standard
for data compression, the Nihon Kogyo Shimbun said.
     Currently, standard teleconferencing systems transmit analog
data at a speed of 150 megabits per second.
     The new system converts and compresses analog information into
7 to 19 megabits of digital signals using an encoder, and transmits
the data into monitors through a decoder which again converts the
digital data into analog signals.
     Mitsubishi plans to set the price for the new system at about 20
million yen, much lower than those of conventional systems, the daily
said.



