<A NAME = "15"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Gov't panel to review fast-breeder reactor project+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     A government advisory panel plans to review Japan's
fast-breeder nuclear power reactor development program following a
coolant leak at a prototype reactor last month, the Asahi Shimbun
newspaper reported Monday.
     The daily said the Atomic Energy Commission, an advisory panel
to the prime minister, will open debate over the issue at a
commission meeting set for Jan. 9.
     It is unprecedented for the commission to review Japan's
national nuclear energy policy, the Asahi said.
     A fast-breeder reactor produces more nuclear fuel than it
consumes, and the technology is the centerpiece of Japan's energy
policy for the 21st century.
     Under the national nuclear energy program, the government aims
to build a demonstration fast-breeder reactor early in the next
century and put fast-breeder reactors into commercial use by around
2030.
     The prototype Monju reactor in the western Japan city of Tsuruga
has been closed down since the Dec. 8 accident in which highly
corrosive sodium leaked from a secondary cooling system.



