U.S. proposes joint R and D for military gear parts+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     The U.S. Defense Department has proposed to its Japanese
counterpart that the two conduct joint research and development of
parts for military equipment in common use in the two countries, a
national daily reported Monday.
     The move seeks to expand the scope of joint development of
defense equipment following the production of a new generation of jet
fighters starting in fiscal 1996, the Yomiuri Shimbun said.
     But two pacifist partners in the tripartite ruling coalition,
including Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama's Social Democratic Party,
may take issue with the move on grounds it could run counter to the
government's policy of banning arms exports, the paper said.
     The Defense Agency is considering limiting the proposed project
to research, stopping short of development, in order to alleviate
such concern, it said.
     The Pentagon proposal, apparently aimed at trimming U.S.
military spending, was advanced during a regular meeting of defense
officials from the two countries on military equipment and
technology, held in Tokyo between late October and early November,
the Yomiuri said..
     Military equipment parts targeted by the project appear to
include electronic components for fighters, antisubmarine planes and
other state-of-the-art hardware, it added.





