January 1, 1996

20 U.S. firms to form joint research-sales base in Japan+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     About 20 big U.S. businesses will jointly establish a research
and sales base in Japan as early as 1997 in an effort to develop
products tailored for Japanese needs, a business daily reported
Monday.
     Of the U.S. companies, seven companies have already decided to
participate in the project.  They include Lockheed Martin Corp., a
major aircraft manufacturer, Timken Co., a bearing maker, and
Caterpillar Inc., a tractor maker, the Nihon Keizai Shimbun said.
     The Japanese government, responding favorably to the move, plans
to extend all-out support for the project through low-interest
funding and tax breaks as it is likely to help reduce Japan's large
trade surplus with the United States, the daily said.
     The project will be formally adopted early this year, the paper
said, adding that among candidate sites for the research-sales base
are Yokohama and Kobe.







