KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Big supermarkets open on New Year's Day+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Daiei Inc., Ito-Yokado Co. and other major supermarkets Monday
opened their stores across the nation on New Year's Day when such
stores have customarily been closed.
     Until last year, supermarket operators had opened their stores
on the second day of the new year while discount and other mass-sales
stores had opened their shops on the first day of the year.
     Supermarkets' moves are targeted primarily at children who
received ''otoshidama'' or New Year's gifts of cash from their
parents and relatives, industry analysts said.
     Daiei, the industry leader, opened 339 of its stores throughout
the country, which account for more than 90% of the total.
     At Tokyo's Himonya store, about 200 people, mostly children and
their parents, queued to buy goods before the opening at 10 a.m.
     Bought actively were personal computers, video game machines and
software, and fresh foods such as vegetables and sushi, store
officials said.
     A housewife, who dropped in at the store after paying her first
visit of the year to a shrine, said, ''It's really convenient because
we no longer need to stock up on food for the New Year's holidays.''



