<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "23"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Alleged shady deal involving housing loan firm revealed+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     One of seven financially crippled housing loan companies took
real estate used as collateral for huge loans to a Tokyo property
concern and its affiliates in the late 1980s for above-market
values, two Japanese dailies reported Monday.
     The Tokyo Shimbun and the Sankei Shimbun said in front-page
stories that Jyuso Inc. and its wholly owned subsidiary had more than
130 billion yen in outstanding loans to the corporate group at the
end of March 1987 when the loans peaked.
     The figure represented 17% of total outstanding loans provided
by Jyuso and its subsidiary, the Sankei said, identifying the real
estate company as Taiyo Estate.
     It could constitute breach of trust for a lender to purchase
real estate provided as collateral for above-market value while
knowing such a deal would result in losses, legal experts said.
     The Sankei said the Taiyo group is run by a relative of a
lawmaker belonging to the Liberal Democratic Party, the biggest group
in the tripartite ruling coalition.
     The Tokyo Shimbun said Jyuso took real estate used as collateral
for the loans to the corporate group between 1990 and 1991 for two to
four times more than the market value, bringing the sum of
outstanding loans to the group to some 42.4 billion yen at the end of
March 1995.
     The market value of the real estate provided as collateral has
fallen sharply since the bursting of the so-called bubble economy, a
stock and real estate boom seen in the late 1980s.
     Jyuso and six other housing loan companies or ''jusen'' have
been tottering under the weight of some 8.1 trillion yen in combined
bad loans as a result of their excessive real estate loans during the
bubble economy.
     The government has decided to set aside some 685 billion yen
under the fiscal 1996 budget for the liquidation of the seven failed
mortgage companies.
     The Asahi Shimbun said Monday law enforcement authorities and
financial regulators will scrutinize financial reports to be
submitted by the seven mortgage companies to decide whether to file
criminal charges against those allegedly involved in the bad loan
problem at the companies starting in early January.
     The national daily said the criminal charges are expected to
include breach of trust, embezzlement and fraud.



