Farm banks lent 5.1 tril. yen to 68 nonbanks, paper says+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Agriculture-related financial institutions which had extended
loans to seven bankrupt housing lenders also supplied 5.1 trillion
yen in loans to 68 other nonbank institutions, a national daily
reported Monday.
     The Yomiuri Shimbun said a list of the nonbanks' creditors which
it had obtained shows that the farm banks had lent more than 2
trillion yen to 27 nonbanks that are now receiving emergency funds
from their founder banks.
     The paper quoted analysts as saying the institutions had lent
money for real estate transactions during the ''bubble economy'' of
the late 1980s and that many of the loans would soon be regarded as
unrecoverable.
     The information is likely to intensify pressure for clarifying
the role that top executives of farm banks played in huge bad loans
at housing loan compnaies, widely known as ''jusen'' in Japan,
according to the newspaper.
     The list shows that among the 68 nonbanks are leasing and
consumer credit companies.
     The daily said the large creditors include the Shizuoka
prefectural association of agricultural credit cooperatives, which
loaned 55.1 billion yen, and the Hyogo prefectural association of
agricultural credit cooperatives, which extended 51.5 billion yen in
loans.
     The National Mutual Insurance Federation of Agricultural
Cooperatives (Zenkyoren) and the prefectural associations of mutual
insurance agricultural cooperatives across the nation extended a
total of 720.3 billion yen, while Norinchikin Bank extended 551.9
billion yen, the paper said.
     On the borrower side, Japan Leasing Corp. received the largest
amount of loans, totaling 456.2 billion yen, it said.



