Daiwa Bank eyes plea-bargaining with U.S. authorities+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Scandal-tainted Daiwa Bank plans to enter into plea-bargaining
as early as next month with U.S. federal law-enforcement authorities
over 24 counts of criminal fraud filed against it, a national daily
reported Monday.
     The fraud charges, filed by federal prosecutors in November,
including allegations of tampering with bank records and misleading
regulators, could subject the Osaka-based commercial bank to as much
as 1.3 billion dollars in fines.
     The Asahi Shimbun, quoting a Daiwa Bank official, said in a
front-page story that Daiwa hopes to bring the case to a settlement
through the plea-bargaining by the end of March when it closes its
books for fiscal 1995.
     Meanwhile, an official of Sumitomo Bank, another major
commercial bank that is taking over U.S. operations of Daiwa,
reportedly said Sumitomo plans to begin talks with Daiwa on their
possible merger in specific terms as early as April after the
conclusion of such bargaining.
     In November, the U.S. Federal Reserve expelled Daiwa Bank from
the United States for allegedly trying to disguise 1.1 billion
dollars in losses due to fraudulent U.S. Treasury bond trading by
Toshihide Iguchi, a trader at its New York branch, over an 11-year
period from 1984.
     In its documents to be submitted to U.S. regulators Jan. 8,
Daiwa Bank is expected to plead not guilty to the fraud charges but
is unlikely to be found not guilty, the daily said.



