January 1, 1996

Sri Lankan president promises 'new beginning' for Jaffna+

COLOMBO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     President Chandrika Kumaratunga in a New Year's message has
promised the people of northern Jaffna that the government will set
up a civil administration in the former rebel stronghold as soon as
possible so they can return to their homes and accustomed lifestyles.
     There is no need for the government to continue maintaining a
military administration in Jaffna, said the president, adding her
government will lay the foundation for a new era with the arrival of
Thai Pongal on Jan. 15, the beginning of the Hindu month of Thai.
     An estimated 200,000 civilians are alleged to have been coerced
by the Tamil Tiger guerrillas to leave Jaffna as government troops
involved in operation ''Riviresa,'' launched Oct. 17 to capture
Jaffna, began advancing toward the city in the north.
     The displaced are now housed in makeshift accommodation in
Vanni, south of the Jaffna Peninsula, where the Tigers have relocated
themselves.
     ''If the military victory achieved should become a victory of
the people, it should be transformed into a victory of peace,
strengthening the sociopolitical field in its entirety,'' said the
president.
     Meanwhile, seven security personnel were killed in two separate
incidents in the island's north and north-central provinces in the
24-hour period ending noon Monday, military officials said.
     Five soldiers were killed and five others injured when the
tractor they were traveling in was blown up by a guerrilla pressure
mine in Kopay north in the northern Jaffna Peninsula Sunday evening,
the Defense Ministry reported.
     The Tamil Tiger rebels are said to have laid several mines
before fleeing the area in the face of advancing government troops.
     In a second incident, Tigers attacked a police post at
Puliyankulam in the north-central province, killing two policemen and
injuring two others, the ministry said.
     Dislodged from their northern Jaffna base Dec. 2, the Tigers
have turned to other vulnerable targets.



