January 1, 1996

6 die, more than 700 injured in New Year's revelry+

MANILA, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     At least six people were killed and more than 700 others
injured, mostly from powerful firecrackers or gunshots, during New
Year's revelry in the Philippines, health officials said Monday.
     Police said two of the killings took place in the southern
cities of Iligan and Ozamis.
     Reports reaching the Health Department said at least 700 people
were rushed to 52 hospitals nationwide for treatment from burns and
gunshot wounds.
     Health Secretary Hilarion Ramiro told a news conference that a
total of 478 people were injured by explosives and 34 were hit by
stray bullets despite a government ban on the use of powerful
firecrackers and guns to greet the new year.
     He said at least 74 revelers sustained stab wounds and 115
others were injured in road accidents.
     At least 29 others were reported injured in some southern
provinces, including a 6-month-old baby girl who was accidentally hit
by a firecracker thrown by her elder brother, police said.
     Fires, sparked by exploding firecrackers, razed markets, houses
and offices in the capital and provinces, reports said.
     Ramiro noted a 50% decrease in the number of fireworks-related
accidents this year.  Last year, he said more than a dozen people
died and at least 4,500 people were injured in welcoming the new
year.
     Filipinos usually light powerful firecrackers and pyrotechnics
at the start of the new year to scare away evil spirits and invite
good luck.




