<A NAME = "33"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Pessimism growing in Pakistan, says Gallup+

ISLAMABAD, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Despair is on the rise in Pakistan, although it still lies at
the halfway point on a listing of countries optimistic or
pessimistic about the future, a Gallup survey shows.
     Five years ago, the pessimists were negligible with less than
10% of those Pakistanis polled expressing pessimism and the
optimists standing at 70%.
     But the latest survey by Gallup Pakistan has found the number
of pessimists has increased to 26% against the 46% who believe the
new year will be better than the one just ended.
     The report said 39% of the people interviewed believe
that Pakistan will witness more violence and troubles in 1996.
     ''It seems that Pakistanis are turning inward.  They are
somewhat hopeful about their immediate environment but suffer from
despair about the national economy,'' the survey said.
     The survey was based on a sample of 1,000 households belonging
to a cross section of income, education and linguistic backgrounds.
It was conducted as part of an international survey by Gallup
International to list ''optimistic'' and ''pessimistic'' countries of
the world.
     Pakistan was 20th among 21 countries found to be optimistic
while Japan was found to be among the major pessimistic nations.
     A pessimistic country was defined as one where less than 40% of
the people believe 1996 will be better than 1995.  Only 21% of those
polled in Japan believed the new year will be better than 1995,
according to the survey.
     In fact Japanese people are found to be the world's fourth most
pessimistic people after Hungary where only 7% of the people were
optimistic, Austria at 14% and the Netherlands at 15%.



