KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Kim Jong Il again fails to give New Year's message+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     North Korea's de facto leader Kim Jong Il failed to deliver a
New Year's message Monday for the second year in a row.
     His father Kim Il Sung, who died in July 1994, used to give an
annual New Year's announcement on the first day of a year.
     In place of such a message, wide coverage was given to a New
Year's Day editorial stressing North Korea's achievements amid
adversity and calling for unity in 1996.
     Calling for uniting ''closely around the Workers Party of Korea
Central Committee headed by comrade Kim Jong Il,'' the editorial,
which was broadcast throughout the nation, was entitled ''Let us
advance vigorously in the new year, flying the red flag,'' according
to a report of the Korean Central News Agency monitored in Tokyo.
     ''Last year the internal and external situation of our
revolution was very rigorous.  The imperialists and reactionaries
persistently tried to isolate our republic...,'' said the joint
editorial by the ruling party's Rodong Sinmun daily, the army
newspaper Joson Inmingun and the Rodong Chongyon paper for youth.
     ''All the victory and achievements gained in the revolution and
construction last year are very valuable and proud because they were
won in face of the acute political and military confrontation with
the enemy, persistent economic blockade and unprecedented natural
disaster,'' said the editorial.
     North Korea, which was already suffering a food shortage, was
hit by massive floods in July and August last year.
     A U.N. report said North Korea's worst flooding in 100 years
left some 500,000 people homeless and destroyed nearly half the
country's farmland, or 1.2 million hectares.
     ''The great victory and achievements were possible only under
the tested leadership of comrade Kim Jong Il.
     ''We must defend respected comrade Kim Jong Il...at the risk of
our lives...He is the publicly recognized leader of our party and
people...is also our eternal supreme commander,'' the editorial said.
     Kim Jong Il has yet to officially take over two of his father's
top titles, president of North Korea and general secretary of the
Workers Party of Korea.
     The editorial said the party's stand of reunifying the Korean
Peninsula ''in a peaceful way'' remains unchanged, reiterating that
reunification ''is possible only by the confederation formula''
comprising the communist North and the capitalist South.
     However, it accused South Korea and its main backer, the United
States, of having ''brought the situation to a hopeless phase.''
     ''No matter how the world situation may change, our party will
steadfastly maintain the banner of socialism, the banner of
independence against imperialism,'' it added.
     Radio Pyongyang reported at 8 a.m. that there would be an
important broadcast on TV and radio starting at 9 a.m.  The broadcast
carried the joint editorial.
     Meanwhile, the name of China's paramount leader Deng Xiaoping
was missing from among the list of Chinese leaders with whom Kim Jong
Il exchanged congratulatory New Year's messages, the monitoring
agency Radiopress said Monday.
     Radio Pyongyang listed in a broadcast the same day names of
foreign government and party leaders with whom Kim had exchanged New
Year's greetings, with the names of Chinese leaders introduced first.
     President Jiang Zemin, Premier Li Peng and National People's
Congress Chairman Qiao Shi were among them but Deng's name was not
mentioned.
     Last year Radio Pyongyang gave Deng's name top billing,
Radiopress said.



