TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     The Atlanta Centennial Games this summer will probably serve as
less of a nostalgic return to the past and more a symbol of how much
has changed in the Olympic movement.
     When the inaugural Games opened 100 years ago in the Greek
capital of Athens, 360 athletes from 13 countries competed in the
male-only event.
     Come this July, as many as 15,000 athletes and officials,
including an anticipated record high 3,700-plus women, are expected
to converge on the southeast U.S. city.
     Furthermore, as the Olympic family has grown into 197 national
Olympic committees (NOCs), 196 of them have accepted invitations to
Atlanta.
     If North Korea also participates, it will be the first time for
an Olympics to feature every NOC.
     Whatever North Korea's position, Atlanta will easily surpass the
previous record set at the Barcelona Games in 1992, with 169 nations
and territories participating.
     The Olympic Charter notwithstanding, politics has certainly
played a big role in the vagaries of the Olympic movement.
     Three Olympic Games -- 1916 scheduled for Berlin, 1940 scheduled
for Tokyo and 1994 scheduled for London -- were canceled because of
the two world wars.
     The Cold War too cast dark clouds over the Olympic movement as
both the 1980 Games, which took place in Moscow, and the 1984
Olympics in Los Angeles were targets of boycotts and counterboycotts.
     The Soviet Union's breakup in 1991 also jacked up the number of
NOCs.  Come this July, Russia and the other new republics, which
entered under one flag at Barcelona, will compete as separate nations
for the first time at Atlanta.
     The Olympic Games have also undergone radical changes under
International Olympic Committee (IOC) President Juan Antonio
Samaranch, who has led the Olympic movement since 1980.
     Instead of celebrating amateurism in sports, the Olympic Games
have inched toward professionalism in recent years under Samaranch's
vow to make Olympics a showcase of the world's best athletes in all
sports.
     In addition to the U.S. basketball ''Dream Team'' of National
Basketball Association (NBA) stars, which grabbed the gold medal at
Barcelona, top world professionals in athletics, cycling, volleyball
and other sports will fight for the limelight in Atlanta.
     The changes do not end there.
     While former IOC head Avery Brundage once boasted during his
20-year reign that the Olympics could survive without television, the
cash-rich electronic media has turned the Games into a multibillion
dollar marketing affair.
     In December, the U.S. television network NBC announced a record
2.3 billion dollar deal to gain the U.S. broadcasting rights for
three Olympics through the year 2008, well before the actual venues
have been decided.
     Dick Pound, the IOC executive in charge of new financial
sources, says the NBC contract will provide long-term financial
stability to the Olympic movement, which once was on the brink of
bankruptcy almost two decades ago.
     The fact that the Centennial Games will be held not in the
Olympic birthplace of Athens but in the United States -- the well
spring of the largest chunk of Olympic sponsorship money -- is
perhaps indicative of the trends to come.
     Of the 10 current member corporations of TOP (the Olympic
Program) -- the IOC's worldwide sponsorship progam -- nine of them,
including Coca-Coca, Xerox and Sports Illustrated, are based in the
U.S.
     The only exception is Matsushita Electric Industrial Co., which
is based in Japan.
     Atlanta Games organizers are also depending on a huge amount of
corporate support, with nearly 30% of its 1.61 billion dollars
in projected revenues expected to come from sponsorship deals.
     Despite rumors that Atlanta is having trouble gathering
corporate funding, A.D. Frazier, chief operating officer of the
Atlanta Committee for the Olympic Games (ACOG), said they do not
expect a significant shortfall.
     ''Ticket sales are exceeding our expectations, so as a whole we
have been successful,'' Frazier said in an interview with Kyodo News.
     Frazier, however, conceded that lack of public funding has posed
a burden, saying, ''We aren't using tax money so we have to be even
more prudent with our budget.''
     One example is AGOC's decision earlier this year to abandon
plans to build an amphitheater, which would hold concerts featuring
stars like James Brown and Gloria Estefan.
     According to Frazier, the biggest challenge facing the Atlanta
organizers now is managing a personnel structure that will balloon
from 3,000 workers to 70,000, ranging from volunteer shuttle bus
drivers to marathon competition officials.
     ''What concerns us most is how to organize the staff, train
them, and where to place them,'' he said.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "40"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Foreign sportsmen indispensable -- up to a point+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Foreign athletes are an indispensable part of professional
sports in contemporary Japan, but their presence is sometimes
regarded as a double-edged sword.
     The presence of foreign players is felt most acutely in Japanese
soccer, where the quality of the J.League would drop markedly without
the skills of the foreigners.
     Ever since the league started in 1993, foreign players, led by
Zico of the Kashima Antlers, have captured the imagination of
Japanese fans as the sport knows no national boundaries.
     In a match at the National Stadium in October between a Japanese
selection and foreigners playing in the league, the fans cheered the
foreign players as much as they did the Japanese.
     But the league has set a limit for foreign players -- five per
team and only three on the pitch at any one time lest the league be
monopolized by them, soccer officials said.
     In baseball too, foreign pitchers have particularly shone in the
recent season with Kip Gross of the Nippon Ham Fighters notching 16
wins to capture the Pacific League's most wins title -- the first
time for a foreigner.
     Eric Hillman of the Chiba Lotte Marines posted 12 wins to
contribute to the team's fine showing, while Robinson Checo of the
Hiroshima Toyo Carp was regarded as a new pitching sensation.
     Except for the Orix BlueWave, all 12 Japanese teams had foreign
pitchers on their rosters when the season started in April since the
quota of foreign players to be registered was expanded by one to
three in 1994, provided that the third is a pitcher.
     Through the introduction of foreign players, each baseball team
or soccer club is hoping to boost its overall ability and improve the
quality of Japanese players.
     But J.League officials have no intention of increasing the
number of foreigners allowed to play in Japan, while Central League
President Hiromori Kawashima still espouses the idea that ''Japanese
baseball should be controlled by Japanese players.''
     In team sports, the bottom line for Japanese fans is to see
their favorite club win, and as long as it does it is not so
important to them who hits the home runs or scores the goals,
according to sports sources.
     But in individual sports the situation of foreign athletes is a
little different.
     In sumo, although there is no set quota, some Japan Sumo
Association officials were once alarmed by the ''encroachment'' of
foreign wrestlers headed by yokozuna Akebono and ozeki Musashimaru.
     Although the officials' apprehensions have so far proved to be
needless owing to the dominance of yokozuna Takanohana, the officials
want to see each stable exercise ''restraint'' and not seek to raise
too many foreign wrestlers.
     To suit the taste of the tradition-bound association, top
foreign wrestlers have no choice but to observe the famous adage ''If
you can't beat them, join them'' -- and Akebono and Musashimaru, both
Americans, have applied for Japanese citizenship, following in the
footsteps of Konishiki.
     In pro boxing, three of the nation's five world champions are
foreigners, and their Japanese managers are having a hard time
promoting their fights in Japan.
     None of the title fights of World Boxing Association lightweight
champion Orzubek Nazarov of Kyrgyzstan was televised live in Japan as
potential Japanese sponsors showed little interest in his fights for
two reasons -- he is not Japanese and is too strong.
     Nazarov's stablemate and World Boxing Council flyweight kingpin
Yuri Arbachakov of Russia is luckier since either Tokyo Broadcasting
System (TBS) or Television Tokyo has televised all of his seven title
defenses so far.
     If Arbachakov, who at first glance looks Japanese, were in fact
Japanese, his would be a household name.  Casual boxing fans appear
uninterested in these foreign-born champions no matter how strong
they may be, boxing sources said.
     Both Nazarov and Arbachakov once adopted Japanese fighting names
after well-known Japanese boxers to make it easier for their managers
to sell tickets.
     But to the average Japanese, foreigners are foreigners under any
name, and the two boxers eventually reverted to their real names.



