January 1, 1996

Four Japanese selected as Atlanta sacred flame runners+

ATLANTA, Dec. 31 Kyodo

     Four Japanese nationals have been selected as sacred flame
runners for the Atlanta Olympic Games in July.
     One pair -- Yoshinobu Nagano and Yumi Kunimoto -- were chosen
after a road race held Sunday at Atlanta and the other pair -- Makoto
Saito and Yoshiko Yagi -- won the honors after a swimming contest
held on the day in Yokohama, Japan.
     Nagano, 38, a native of Kumamoto Prefecture, and Kunimoto, 35,
from Kanagawa Prefecture, are both residents of Atlanta.



<A HREF ="#HeadList">Back to Headline List</A><BR>
<HR>
<A NAME = "43"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Nagoya beats Hiroshima 3-0 to win soccer Emperor's Cup+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo

     Takafumi Ogura scored twice and Takashi Hirano added a third as
Nagoya Grampus Eight blanked Sanfrecce Hiroshima to win the 75th
Emperor's Cup on New Year's Day on Monday.
     Nagoya dominated the entire match in a final between the two
J.League clubs to capture its first all-Japan championship contested
by all soccer clubs in Japan, 2,800 in all.
     ''The team played very well in the past year.  It is just an
award for them,'' said Nagoya's French manager Arsene Wenger after
the match at Tokyo's National Stadium.
     Nagoya, which finished as runner-up in the J.League second stage
last season, opened the scoring in the 18th minute as Hirano set up a
beautiful short pass which Ogura volleyed home from just outside the
penalty box.
     The rampaging Grampus Eight pumped in two fast goals early in
the second half to seal the victory, with both goals set up by
Yugoslav striker Drajan Stojkovic, last season's J.League Player of
the Year.
     The second Nagoya goal came in the 52th minute when Ogura, the
22-year-old Japan international, picked up a loose ball Hiroshima
goalkeeper Kazuya Maekawa deflected from a Stojkovic attempt and
slotted it home from close range.
     Before the Sanfreece team can recover from the shell shock,
Nagoya turned the score 3-0 one minute later as Hirano fired home a
cross-field pass from Stojkovic.
     Lines-up:
     Nagoya -- Yuji Ito, Seiichi Ogawa, Go Oiwa, Kazuhisa Iijima,
Torres, Tetsuya Okayama (Yasuyuki Moriyama, 85th minute), Franck
Durix, Tetsuya Asano, Takashi Hirano (Naoki Mori, 89th minute),
Drajan Stojkovic, Takafumi Ogura (Tetsuo Nakanishi, 73th minute).
     Hiroshima -- Kazuya Maekawa, Hiroshige Yanagimoto, Mitsuaki
Kojima, Kenichi Uemura, Ryuji Michiki, Hajime Moriyasu, Pieter
Huistra (Tsutomu Ogi, 61st minute), Masato Fue (Yoshiro Moriyama,
61st minute), Hiroyoshi Kuwabara, Noh Jung Youn, Takuya Takagi.
     Attendance: 47,021.



