January 1, 1996

Kyodo news summary+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo


     -- Emperor Akihito said he hopes the New Year will be more
fortunate than 1995, which was overshadowed in Japan by January's
Great Hanshin Earthquake and March's nerve gas attack on Tokyo
subways.
     -- Emperor Akihito, in unusual candor, expressed his personal
impressions in his ''waka'' poems of the aftermath of the Jan. 17
Great Hanshin Earthquake, and Okinawa and Hiroshima 50 years after
the end of World War II.
     -- Prime Minister Murayama pledged to do his utmost in 1996 for
the recovery of the Japanese economy by promoting deregulation and
helping develop new businesses to create new jobs.
     -- South Korean President Kim called on the nation to work to
make South Korea a first-class country, pledging he would be at the
forefront of such efforts.
     -- A Japanese-U.S. joint venture has won a 25 million dollar
order for building a liquid radioactive waste facility in Russia's
Far East, Itar-Tass news agency reported.
     -- Japan's ''Big Two'' automakers, Toyota Motor Corp. and Nissan
Motor Co., are in negotiations to enter into a tie-up in the area of
forklifts in North America, an industrial daily reported.
     -- More than 1,100 people have already decided to run in the
next general election, the first poll for the House of
Representatives since a new system combining single-seat
constituencies with proportional representation was put into effect a
year ago, according to a Kyodo News survey.
     -- Births in Japan continued their 20-year downward trend in
1995, while the number of deaths, inflated by January's huge
earthquake, topped 900,000 for the first time since 1950, the Health
and Welfare Ministry announced.



