<A NAME = "45"></A>Copyright
KYODO NEWS SERVICE via NewsNet
January 1, 1996

Kyodo news summary -2-+

TOKYO, Jan. 1 Kyodo


     -- NEC Corp. will start construction of its second U.S.
semiconductor plant in California as early as spring at a cost of 80
billion to 100 billion yen in a move aimed at taking the lead in the
global market for 256-megabit dynamic random access memory (DRAM)
chips, a business daily reported.
     -- The Atlantic Centennial Games this summer will probably serve
as less of a nostalgic return to the past and more a symbol of how
much has changed in the Olympic movement. (News Focus)
     -- Goods worth several million dollars are estimated to have been
gutted in a fire at a Karachi Port warehouse in the worst blaze at
the port in 10 years, port officials said.
     -- Sri Lankan President Kumaratunga in a New Year's message has
promised the people of northern Jaffna that the government will set up
a civilian administration in the former rebel stronghold as soon as
possible so they can return to their homes and accustomed lifestyles.
     -- Maybe it is part of the recent trend in Japan to shift to a
plainer lifestyle in the prolonged recession, or it could be a sign
that more men recognize the need to be self-supporting later in life
as people live longer than before and as more women go out to work,
leaving their husbands at home. (Feature)
     -- The governor of Kochi Prefecture on Japan's smallest main
island of Shikoku reiterated his intention this year to scrap a
regulation that makes Japanese nationality a prerequisite for entry
into prefectural public service.
     -- One of seven financially crippled housing loan companies took
real estate used as collateral for huge loans for above-market
values, two Japanese dailies reported.



